==Chinese==

===Etymology 1===
From the hotkey in many video games associated with the command "attack".

====Pronunciation====
{{zh-pron
|m=ēi
|cat=v
}}

====Verb====
{{zh-verb}}

# {{lb|zh|slang|neologism}} to [[attack]]; to [[assault]]
# {{lb|zh|slang|neologism}} to [[pursue]] romantically

====See also====
* {{zh-l|平A}}
* {{zh-l|對A}}

===Etymology 2===
Initialism of {{bor-lite|zh|en|available}}.

====Pronunciation====
{{zh-pron
|c=ei1
|cat=a
}}

====Adjective====
{{head-lite|zh|adjectives}}

# {{lb|zh|Hong Kong Cantonese|slang}} single, open to a relationship

=====Derived terms=====
* {{l-lite|zh|A0}}
* {{l-lite|zh|A380}}

===Etymology 3===
From the letter A of the English pattern playing cards. Various names exist for this symbol in the spoken language.
; Mandarin ''jiān''
: From {{zh-l|尖|tip}}, because the letter A has an upward tip.
; Cantonese ''jin1''
: {{clipping|yue|煙士|tr=jin1 si6-2}}, from {{bor-lite|yue|en|ace}}.

====Pronunciation====
{{zh-pron
|m=jiān
|c=jin1
|cat=n
}}

====Noun====
{{head-lite|zh|nouns}}

# {{lb|zh|card games}} [[ace]] {{zh-mw|隻|張}}

=====Synonyms=====
{{zh-dial|尖兒}}

===Etymology 4===

====Pronunciation 1====
