====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To [[obtain]] or [[seize]] by [[violence]].
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[devour]] with great [[eagerness]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1938|author=P.G. Woodhouse|title=The Code of the Woosters|passage=I refer to the danger of keeping a dog of this nature and disposition in a bedroom, where it can spring out '''ravening''' on anyone who enters.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[prey]] on with [[rapacity]].
#: ''The raven is both a [[scavenger]], who '''ravens''' a dead animal almost like a vulture, and a [[bird of prey]], who commonly '''ravens''' to catch a rodent.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To show [[rapacity]]; to be [[greedy]] (''for'' something).
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1587|author={{w|Leonard Mascall}}|title=The First Booke of Cattell|location=London|chapter=The nature and qualities of hogges, and also the gouernement thereof|url=http://name.umdl.umich.edu/A07176.0001.001
|passage={{...}} because hogs are commonly '''rauening''' for their meat, more then other cattel, it is meet therefore to haue them ringed, or else they wil doe much hurt in digging and turning vp corne fieldes {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1852|author={{w|Elizabeth Gaskell}}|chapter=The Old Nurse’s Story|title=The Old Nurse’s Story and Other Tales|url=http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks06/0605581h.html
|passage=They passed along towards the great hall-door, where the winds howled and '''ravened''' for their prey {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1865|author={{w|Sabine Baring-Gould}}|title=The Book of Were-Wolves|location=London|publisher=Smith, Elder & Co.|chapter=8|page=114|url=https://archive.org/details/bookwerewolvesb00barigoog
|passage=The Greek were-wolf is closely related to the vampire. The lycanthropist falls into a cataleptic trance, during which his soul leaves his body, enters that of a wolf and '''ravens''' for blood.}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1931|author={{w|J. B. Fagan|James B. Fagan}}|title=The Improper Duchess|location=London|publisher=Victor Gollancz|year_published=1932|section=Act 3, p. 237|url=http://fadedpage.com/books/20111103/html.php
|passage=On one side the great temple where you can gather the good harvest—on the other a dirty little scandal that you’ve nosed out to fling to paper scavengers who feed it to their readin’ millions '''ravening''' for pornographic dirt.}}

