==English==

===Etymology===
{{der|en|la|-}} {{compound|la|floccus|t1=a wisp|naucum|t2=a trifle|nihilum|t3=nothing|pilus|t4=a hair|nocat=1}} + {{m|en|-fication}}

A jocular coinage, apparently by pupils at {{w|Eton College}},<ref>{{cite-web |title=''Floccinaucinihilipilification'' |publisher=''The Spectator'' |work=Mind your language |author=Dot Wordsworth |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2011/06/mind-your-language-39/ |date=11 June 2011}}.</ref> combining a number of Latin word stems. The word was inspired by a line in the ''Eton Latin Grammar'' (published in the early 19th century), in which some nouns commonly used in the [[genitive]] case with some verbs like {{m|la|pendo}} and {{m|la|facio}} are listed, which express evaluating something as worthless or as previously mentioned:

"{{l|la|flocci|Flócci}} ''of a lock of wool,'' {{l|la|nauci|náuci}} ''of a nut-shell'', {{l|la|nihili|níhili}} ''of nóthing'', {{l|la|pili|píli}} ''of a hair'', {{l|la|assis|ássis}} ''of a pénny'', {{l|la|huius|hújus}} ''of this'', {{l|la|teruncii|terúncii}} ''of a fárthing'', addúntur ''are ádded'', peculiáritèr ''pecúliarly or véry próperly'' vérbis ''to verbs'' æstimándi ''of esteéming''."<ref>{{cite-book|author=T.W.C. Edwards|chapter=RULES of SYNTAX construed|title=Eton College Grammar: A Plain and Concise Introduction to the Latin Language, being Lily's Grammar Abridged|url=https://archive.org/details/etonlatingramma02collgoog/page/n6/mode/2up|year=1826|page=269|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/etonlatingramma02collgoog/page/n282/mode/2up}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˌflɒksɪˌnɔːsɪˌnaɪhɪlɪˌpɪlɪfɪˈkeɪʃən/|/ˌflɒksiˌnɒsiˌnɪhɪlɪˌpɪlɪfɪˈkeɪʃən/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-floccinaucinihilipilification.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|en-uk-floccinaucinihilipilification.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
{{attention|en|Neither audio pronunciation matches either IPA pronunciation. There would appear to be four logical combinations using either "nɒsɪ" vs "nɔːsɪ" in one position and "nɪ" vs "naɪ" immediately following. The IPA gives only two of the four possibilities and the audio gives only the other two of the four possibilities.}}
* {{hyph|en| flocci|nauci|ni|hili|pili|fi|ca|tion}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# {{lb|en|often|humorous}} The act or habit of describing or regarding something as [[unimportant]], of having no value or being [[worthless]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1741|author=[[w:William Shenstone|William Shenstone]]|title=Letters|passage=I loved him for nothing so much as his '''flocci-nauci-nihili-pili-fication''' of money.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1970|author=[[w:Patrick O'Brian|Patrick O'Brian]]|title=Master and Commander|passage=There is a systematic '''flocci-nauci-nihili-pilification''' of all other aspects of existence that angers me.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2000|author=Raymond J. Chambers|title=Logic, Law, and Ethics|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Ei03tgPKEKcC&lpg=PA28&dq=floccinaucinihilipilification&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q=floccinaucinihilipilification&f=false|passage='''Floccinaucinihilipilification''' in accounting - does it matter?}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=Sol Steinmetz|title=The life of language|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=raN6AAAAIAAJ&q=floccinaucinihilipilification&dq=floccinaucinihilipilification&hl=en&sa=X&ei=dS8BU4bIMcTWyQHf94GwDw&ved=0CKsBEOgBMBc4PA|passage=They must be taken with an air of contempt, a '''floccinaucinihilipilification''' of all that can gratify the outward man.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2009|author=Judith Orloff|title=Emotional Freedom|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=_V53VntvlmQC&lpg=PA312&dq=floccinaucinihilipilification&pg=PA312#v=onepage&q=floccinaucinihilipilification&f=false|passage=Some people with low self-esteem are prone to '''floccinaucinihilipilification''', the habit of deeming everything worthless.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2011|author=Bruce Ratner|title=Statistical and Machine-Learning Data Mining|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=I3KZCfmhWJwC&lpg=PT42&dq=floccinaucinihilipilification&pg=PT42#v=onepage&q=floccinaucinihilipilification&f=false|passage=The quasi statistician would doubtlessly not know how to check this supposition, thus rendering the interpretation of the mean profit as '''floccinaucinihilipilification'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012|author=[[w:Jacob Rees-Mogg|Jacob Rees-Mogg]]|title=Hansard|url=http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201212/cmhansrd/cm120221/debtext/120221-0002.htm#12022155000158|passage=Let me indulge in the '''floccinaucinihilipilification''' of EU judges and quote from the book of Amos about them.}}

====Usage notes====
Often cited as the longest non-technical word in the English language, being one letter longer than the commonly cited {{m|en|antidisestablishmentarianism}}. It is the longest word ever recorded by Hansard after Conservative MP Jacob Rees-Mogg used the word in Parliament on 21 February 2012.<ref>
{{cite-web
|date=21 February 2012
|author=Jacob Rees-Mogg
|authorlink=Jacob Rees-Mogg
|title=HC Deb, 21 February 2012, c787
|work=TheyWorkForYou
|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2012-02-21b.787.1
|passage=It does not apply to judges in the EU, so let me be rude about them. Let me indulge in the floccinaucinihilipilification of EU judges and quote from the book of Amos about them: {{...}}}}
</ref>

